Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation:

**1. Register the route**
```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("productdetails", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate — simple string vs. complex object**
```csharp
// ProductListViewModel.cs
[RelayCommand]
async Task OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    // Approach A – primitive string parameter
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"productdetails?id={product.Id}");

    // Approach B – pass the full object via dictionary
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("productdetails", new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        ["product"] = product
    });
}
```

**3. Receive data with `IQueryAttributable` on the ViewModel**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsViewModel.cs
public partial class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    [ObservableProperty] string productId;
    [ObservableProperty] Product product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A – simple string
        if (query.TryGetValue("id", out var id))
            ProductId = id.ToString();

        // Approach B – full object (passed via dictionary overload)
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
            Product = p;
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page**
```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String param | Object param |
|---|---|---|
| **Navigation call** | URI query string `?id=...` | `Dictionary<string, object>` overload |
| **Received as** | `object` (string under the hood) | The original typed object |
| **Survives deep-link URLs** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (requires in-process navigation) |

Use **string parameters** for deep-linkable, serializable values. Use the **dictionary overload** when you need the full object and don't need URI-based deep linking.
